INSERT INTO Books VALUES(62,'Red Rising','Pierce Brown','Del Rey','Fiction','Fiction','Del Rey','2014-01-28','','English','English Speculative','9780345539786','NEW YORK TIMES BESTSELLER ΓÇó Pierce BrownΓÇÖs relentlessly entertaining debut channels the excitement of The Hunger Games by Suzanne Collins and EnderΓÇÖs Game by Orson Scott Card. ΓÇ£Red Rising ascends above a crowded dys┬¡topian field.ΓÇ¥ΓÇöUSA Today ONE OF THE BEST BOOKS OF THE YEARΓÇöEntertainment Weekly, BuzzFeed, Shelf Awareness ΓÇ£I live for the dream that my children will be born free,ΓÇ¥ she says. ΓÇ£That they will be what they like. That they will own the land their father gave them.ΓÇ¥ ΓÇ£I live for you,ΓÇ¥ I say sadly. Eo kisses my cheek. ΓÇ£Then you must live for more.ΓÇ¥ Darrow is a Red, a member of the lowest caste in the color-coded society of the future. Like his fellow Reds, he works all day, believing that he and his people are making the surface of Mars livable for future generations. Yet he toils willingly, trusting that his blood and sweat will one day result in a better world for his children. But Darrow and his kind have been betrayed. Soon he discovers that humanity reached the surface generations ago. Vast cities and lush wilds spread across the planet. DarrowΓÇöand Reds like himΓÇöare nothing more than slaves to a decadent ruling class. Inspired by a longing for justice, and driven by the memory of lost love, Darrow sacrifices everything to infiltrate the legendary Institute, a proving ground for the dominant Gold caste, where the next generation of humanityΓÇÖs overlords struggle for power. He will be forced to compete for his life and the very future of civilization against the best and most brutal of SocietyΓÇÖs ruling class. There, he will stop at nothing to bring down his enemies . . . even if it means he has to become one of them to do so. Praise for Red Rising ΓÇ£[A] spectacular adventure . . . one heart-pounding ride . . . Pierce BrownΓÇÖs dizzyingly good debut novel evokes The Hunger Games, Lord of the Flies, and EnderΓÇÖs Game. . . . [Red Rising] has everything it needs to become meteoric.ΓÇ¥ΓÇöEntertainment Weekly ΓÇ£Ender, Katniss, and now Darrow.ΓÇ¥ΓÇöScott Sigler ΓÇ£Red Rising is a sophisticated vision. . . . Brown will find a devoted audience.ΓÇ¥ΓÇöRichmond Times-Dispatch DonΓÇÖt miss any of Pierce BrownΓÇÖs Red Rising Saga: RED RISING ΓÇó GOLDEN SON ΓÇó MORNING STAR ΓÇó IRON GOLD ΓÇó DARK AGE ΓÇó LIGHT BRINGER',1,'1752825069075.0','1752825069075.0','http://books.google.com/books/content?id=pEaTEAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&source=gbs_api',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO Books VALUES(64,'Mexican Gothic','Silvia Moreno-Garcia','National Geographic Books','Fiction','Fiction','National Geographic Books','2020-06-30','','English','English General Fiction','9780525620785','NEW YORK TIMES BESTSELLER ΓÇó ΓÇ£ItΓÇÖs Lovecraft meets the Bront├½s in Latin America, and after a slow-burn start Mexican Gothic gets seriously weird.ΓÇ¥ΓÇöThe Guardian IN DEVELOPMENT AS A HULU ORIGINAL LIMITED SERIES PRODUCED BY KELLY RIPA AND MARK CONSUELOS ΓÇó WINNER OF THE LOCUS AWARD ΓÇó NOMINATED FOR THE BRAM STOKER AWARD ONE OF THE BEST BOOKS OF THE YEAR: The New Yorker, Vanity Fair, NPR, The Washington Post, Tordotcom, Marie Claire, Vox, Mashable, MenΓÇÖs Health, Library Journal, Book Riot, LibraryReads An isolated mansion. A chillingly charismatic aristocrat. And a brave socialite drawn to expose their treacherous secrets. . . . From the author of Gods of Jade and Shadow comes ΓÇ£a terrifying twist on classic gothic horrorΓÇ¥ (Kirkus Reviews) set in glamorous 1950s Mexico. After receiving a frantic letter from her newly-wed cousin begging for someone to save her from a mysterious doom, Noem├¡ Taboada heads to High Place, a distant house in the Mexican countryside. SheΓÇÖs not sure what she will findΓÇöher cousinΓÇÖs husband, a handsome Englishman, is a stranger, and Noem├¡ knows little about the region. Noem├¡ is also an unlikely rescuer: SheΓÇÖs a glamorous debutante, and her chic gowns and perfect red lipstick are more suited for cocktail parties than amateur sleuthing. But sheΓÇÖs also tough and smart, with an indomitable will, and she is not afraid: Not of her cousinΓÇÖs new husband, who is both menacing and alluring; not of his father, the ancient patriarch who seems to be fascinated by Noem├¡; and not even of the house itself, which begins to invade NoemiΓÇÖs dreams with visions of blood and doom. Her only ally in this inhospitable abode is the familyΓÇÖs youngest son. Shy and gentle, he seems to want to help Noem├¡, but might also be hiding dark knowledge of his familyΓÇÖs past. For there are many secrets behind the walls of High Place. The familyΓÇÖs once colossal wealth and faded mining empire kept them from prying eyes, but as Noem├¡ digs deeper she unearths stories of violence and madness. And Noem├¡, mesmerized by the terrifying yet seductive world of High Place, may soon find it impossible to ever leave this enigmatic house behind. ΓÇ£ItΓÇÖs as if a supernatural power compels us to turn the pages of the gripping Mexican Gothic.ΓÇ¥ΓÇöThe Washington Post ΓÇ£Mexican Gothic is the perfect summer horror read, and marks Moreno-Garcia with her hypnotic and engaging prose as one of the genreΓÇÖs most exciting talents.ΓÇ¥ΓÇöNerdist ΓÇ£A period thriller as rich in suspense as it is in lush ΓÇÖ50s atmosphere.ΓÇ¥ΓÇöEntertainment Weekly',1,'1752825095732.0','1752825095732.0','http://books.google.com/books/content?id=mvKNEAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&source=gbs_api',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO Books VALUES(65,'If This Book Exists, You''re in the Wrong Universe','Jason Pargin','St. Martin''s Press','Fiction','Fiction','St. Martin''s Press','2022-10-18','','English','English General Fiction','9781250195821','New York Times bestselling author Jason ParginΓÇÖs hilarious and horrifying John Dies at the End series continues with If This Book Exists, YouΓÇÖre in the Wrong Universe. "Pargin once again delights with scathing social commentary thinly disguised as an outrageous action novel...This is a feast."ΓÇöPublishers Weekly "Within the snarky humor is an incisive commentary on social media and the state of our connected world, and a story about trauma and how people lash out when theyΓÇÖre hurt...This isnΓÇÖt just a funny tale of inept supernatural investigators; itΓÇÖs a story of people struggling through pain to find a better path. Pargin offers us a welcome note of hope." ΓÇö Booklist If the broken neon signs, shuttered storefronts, and sub-standard housing didnΓÇÖt tip you off, youΓÇÖve just wandered into the city of ΓÇ£UndisclosedΓÇ¥. You donΓÇÖt want to be caught dead here, because odds are you just might find yourself rising from the grave. That hasnΓÇÖt stopped tourists from visiting to check out the unusual phenomena that hangs around our town like radioactive fallout. Interdimensional parasites feeding on human hosts, paranormal cults worshipping demonic entities, vengeful teenage sorcerers, weΓÇÖve got it all. Did I mention the possessed toy? ItΓÇÖs a plastic football-sized egg thatΓÇÖs supposed to hatch an adorable, colorful stuffed bird when a child ΓÇ£feedsΓÇ¥ it through a synchronized smartphone app. WhatΓÇÖs actually inside is an otherworldly monstrosity thatΓÇÖs enticing impressionable wayward youth into murdering folks and depositing their body parts inside the egg as if itΓÇÖs a hungry piggy bank to trigger the end of the world. ThatΓÇÖs where Dave, John, and Amy come in. They face supernatural threats so the rest of us donΓÇÖt have toΓÇöand sometimes even earn a couple of bucks to so do. But between the bloody ritual sacrifices and soul-crushing nightmares, our trio realizes this apocalypse is way above their pay grade.',1,'1752825160701.0','1752825160701.0','http://books.google.com/books/content?id=U2tZEAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&source=gbs_api',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO Books VALUES(66,'What the Hell Did I Just Read','David Wong','St. Martin''s Griffin','Fiction','Fiction','St. Martin''s Griffin','2018-09-04','','English','English General Fiction','1250135311','John Dies at the End''s "smart take on fear manages to tap into readers'' existential dread on one page, then have them laughing the next" (Publishers Weekly) and This Book is Full of Spiders was "unlike any other book of the genre" (Washington Post). Now, New York Times bestselling author David Wong is back with What the Hell Did I Just Read, the third installment of this black-humored thriller series. It''s the story "They" don''t want you to read. Though, to be fair, "They" are probably right about this one. To quote the Bible, "Learning the truth can be like loosening a necktie, only to realize it was the only thing keeping your head attached." No, don''t put the book back on the shelf -- it is now your duty to purchase it to prevent others from reading it. Yes, it works with e-books, too, I don''t have time to explain how. While investigating a fairly straightforward case of a shape-shifting interdimensional child predator, Dave, John and Amy realized there might actually be something weird going on. Together, they navigate a diabolically convoluted maze of illusions, lies, and their own incompetence in an attempt to uncover a terrible truth they -- like you -- would be better off not knowing. Your first impulse will be to think that a story this gruesome -- and, to be frank, stupid -- cannot possibly be true. That is precisely the reaction "They" are hoping for.',1,'1752825168380.0','1752825168380.0','http://books.google.com/books/content?id=ynbhswEACAAJ&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&source=gbs_api',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO Books VALUES(67,'This Book Is Full of Spiders','David Wong','Macmillan','Fiction','Fiction','Macmillan','2012-10-02','','English','English General Fiction','9780312546342','Fan favorite Wong takes readers to a whole new level with this blistering sequel to the cult sensation "John Dies at the End," soon to be a movie starring Paul Giamatti.',1,'1752825178625.0','1752825178625.0','http://books.google.com/books/content?id=33y0ntb_zqoC&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&edge=curl&source=gbs_api',NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO Books VALUES(68,'John Dies at the End','Jason Pargin, David Wong','St. Martin''s Griffin','Fiction','Fiction','St. Martin''s Griffin','2021-10-05','','English','English General Fiction','1250830567','John Dies at the End is a genre-bending, humorous account of two college drop-outs inadvertently charged with saving their small townΓÇöand the worldΓÇöfrom a host of supernatural and paranormal invasions. This updated special edition includes commentary from the characters and the author! "[Jason Pargin] has updated the Lovecraft tradition and infused it with humor that rather than lessening the horror, increases it dramatically. Every time I set the book down, I was wary that something really was afoot, that there were creatures I couldn''t see, and that because I suspected this, I was next. Engaging, comic, and terrifying." ΓÇöJoe Garden, Features Editor, The Onion "[Pargin] is like a mash-up of Douglas Adams and Stephen King... ''page-turner'' is an understatement." ΓÇöDon Coscarelli, director, Phantasm I-V, Bubba Ho-tep STOP. You should not have touched this book with your bare hands. NO, don''t put it down. It''s too late. They''re watching you. My name is David. My best friend is John. Those names are fake. You might want to change yours. You may not want to know about the things you''ll read on these pages, about the sauce, about Korrok, about the invasion, and the future. But it''s too late. You touched the book. You''re in the game. You''re under the eye. The only defense is knowledge. You need to read this book, to the end. Even the part with the bratwurst. Why? You just have to trust me. The important thing is this: The sauce is a drug, and it gives users a window into another dimension. John and I never had the chance to say no. You still do. Unfortunately for us, if you make the right choice, we''ll have a much harder time explaining how to fight off the otherworldly invasion currently threatening to enslave humanity. I''m sorry to have involved you in this, I really am. But as you read about these terrible events and the very dark epoch the world is about to enter as a result, it is crucial you keep one thing in mind: None of this was my fault.',1,'1752825191525.0','1752825191525.0','http://books.google.com/books/content?id=RTAvzgEACAAJ&printsec=frontcover&img=1&zoom=1&source=gbs_api',NULL,NULL);
